Well, so notice actually this
is, in a sense, almost exactly

00:32:49.970 --> 00:32:52.700
the same advice that you
would give to somebody

00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:56.870
who was in a domestic
violence situation, somebody

00:32:56.870 --> 00:32:58.130
who is being held hostage--

00:32:58.130 --> 00:32:59.750
extreme language I know--

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:01.550
but the advice is the same.

00:33:01.550 --> 00:33:07.460
Because if you want to salvage
your health and your mental

00:33:07.460 --> 00:33:08.240
well-being--

00:33:08.240 --> 00:33:14.120
60% of people suffer some sort
of mental illness or episode

00:33:14.120 --> 00:33:14.870
at work--

00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:18.840
60%-- but here's the choice.

00:33:18.840 --> 00:33:24.710
You either have to leave,
or you have to overthrow.

00:33:24.710 --> 00:33:27.900
Whistleblowing is really rea--

00:33:27.900 --> 00:33:30.820
I don't know that many
whistleblowers that are,

00:33:30.820 --> 00:33:33.230
you know, glad they did it--

00:33:33.230 --> 00:33:34.910
but it is an option.

00:33:34.910 --> 00:33:37.940
Or you have to endure.

00:33:37.940 --> 00:33:40.160
But if you're going
to endure, you

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:42.248
have to turn it into a positive.

00:33:42.248 --> 00:33:43.790
So the way to turn
it into a positive

00:33:43.790 --> 00:33:46.590
is, OK, I'm working
for a corporapath.

00:33:46.590 --> 00:33:48.260
It's very unpleasant.

00:33:48.260 --> 00:33:49.400
I'm not dying.

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:52.970
What am I learning here, and
for how long will I do this?

00:33:52.970 --> 00:33:55.850
Because anybody can
put up with anything

00:33:55.850 --> 00:33:58.420
for a short period of time.

00:33:58.420 --> 00:33:58.970
OK.

00:33:58.970 --> 00:34:01.620
I will do this for
another six months,

00:34:01.620 --> 00:34:04.550
and then I will see where
I am and make a decision.

00:34:04.550 --> 00:34:07.010
See, you have to
help that person,

00:34:07.010 --> 00:34:09.710
because leaving
probably, you know--

00:34:09.710 --> 00:34:13.219
I mean at some point,
health has to come before.

00:34:13.219 --> 00:34:16.610
If it's a partner,
then one of the things

00:34:16.610 --> 00:34:19.520
is they don't want
to let you down.

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:22.777
If they were on their own,
they'd probably leave.

00:34:22.777 --> 00:34:24.110
But they don't want to let down.

00:34:24.110 --> 00:34:27.860
How many of you feel
obligated to carry

00:34:27.860 --> 00:34:32.239
on earning what you are earning
maybe if your partner is either

00:34:32.239 --> 00:34:35.530
at home and not
earning or has a--

00:34:35.530 --> 00:34:39.290
yeah-- oh, the stories,
the fear that we

00:34:39.290 --> 00:34:42.710
have of going into the unknown.

00:34:42.710 --> 00:34:45.630
Wow.

00:34:45.630 --> 00:34:48.449
We have to make a
positive choice.

00:34:48.449 --> 00:34:49.870
Yeah.

00:34:49.870 --> 00:34:52.620
AUDIENCE: I wonder-- so the
most things that you described

00:34:52.620 --> 00:34:54.360
are on an individual
level, and we all

00:34:54.360 --> 00:34:57.930
know that the only thing we
can change is ourselves first.

00:34:57.930 --> 00:35:00.860
But what could you do on
a more corporate level?

00:35:00.860 --> 00:35:03.940
I mean, what could we do to
create organizations that

00:35:03.940 --> 00:35:07.630
do not enforce those behaviors?

00:35:07.630 --> 00:35:14.830
GARETH CHICK: So I really don't
want to be a harbinger of doom,

00:35:14.830 --> 00:35:21.910
but so many things have been
tried over so many years.

00:35:21.910 --> 00:35:30.020
And corporatism has the most
beautiful survival instinct.

00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:35.740
So governments will change
legislation and say,

00:35:35.740 --> 00:35:38.440
we'll regulate, and this
will bring the corporations

00:35:38.440 --> 00:35:39.370
into line.

00:35:39.370 --> 00:35:43.510
And then armies-- anybody in
here a lawyer or an accountant

00:35:43.510 --> 00:35:48.370
or married to a
lawyer or accountant?

00:35:48.370 --> 00:35:49.120
Ah, what the hell?

00:35:49.120 --> 00:35:50.060
I'll take the risk.

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:55.520
The parasites who feed
off will just create,

00:35:55.520 --> 00:35:58.040
because the
corporation will say,

00:35:58.040 --> 00:36:00.045
well you know, if
we're regulated,

00:36:00.045 --> 00:36:05.600
that will cost us $15
million, or if we're regulated

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:07.790
or we might be fined.

00:36:07.790 --> 00:36:10.900
I mean, organizations
getting fined?

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:12.350
My word.

00:36:12.350 --> 00:36:15.620
So it's worth paying
half a million euros

00:36:15.620 --> 00:36:17.690
to get some legal and
accounting advice,

00:36:17.690 --> 00:36:19.190
and we'll get around it.

00:36:19.190 --> 00:36:22.010
Every single thing, every
single regulation, people

00:36:22.010 --> 00:36:23.420
can get around.

00:36:23.420 --> 00:36:26.880
Now, at some point, because
we're at a tipping point,

00:36:26.880 --> 00:36:29.780
there may be a movement.

00:36:29.780 --> 00:36:34.670
There may be a revolution
of some kind maybe,

00:36:34.670 --> 00:36:39.630
but there's nothing that we as
individuals can do about that.

00:36:39.630 --> 00:36:42.890
We can go on streets,
put on a yellow vest

00:36:42.890 --> 00:36:46.850
or whatever the-- we
can do those things.

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:50.635
But we can change our
piece of the world.

00:36:50.635 --> 00:36:51.400
We can.

00:36:51.400 --> 00:36:55.840
We can say, I'm not
going to do things

00:36:55.840 --> 00:36:58.420
that I know that don't
feel right to me.

00:36:58.420 --> 00:37:01.220
I'm not going to
do them anymore.

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:04.570
And the amazing thing
is that probably

00:37:04.570 --> 00:37:06.130
will get positive
feedback when we

00:37:06.130 --> 00:37:12.370
actually-- because our bosses
want us to be free of fear.

00:37:12.370 --> 00:37:13.630
The crazy thing is--

00:37:13.630 --> 00:37:17.440
I mean, I understand working
for an intimidating boss

00:37:17.440 --> 00:37:21.370
when you anticipate an angry
reaction, that's a horrible,

00:37:21.370 --> 00:37:24.730
and that is abusive.

00:37:24.730 --> 00:37:27.550
But it's even more
intimidating to work for a boss

00:37:27.550 --> 00:37:33.130
that you love and see a look of
disappointment in their eyes.

00:37:33.130 --> 00:37:35.320
Oh my God, I can't have that.

00:37:35.320 --> 00:37:37.030
I can't dis--- yeah.

00:37:37.030 --> 00:37:41.000
And so we put a fear
around ourselves.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.440
The only thing we can
do is ask ourselves,

00:37:44.440 --> 00:37:47.080
what's one thing I could
do this afternoon that

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:49.720
would be more
integral, that would

00:37:49.720 --> 00:37:53.660
be more attached to my moral,
that would be more courageous

00:37:53.660 --> 00:37:54.160
of me?

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:55.390
Go do it.

00:37:55.390 --> 00:38:00.120
And the world would do
what it's going to do.

00:38:00.120 --> 00:38:03.740
Don't think we should sound
fatalistic and yet I have.

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:06.585
We have time for, oh, yes
just two or three more.

00:38:06.585 --> 00:38:07.396
Yeah.

00:38:07.396 --> 00:38:09.740
AUDIENCE: So can you tell
us more about the turning

00:38:09.740 --> 00:38:13.370
point from a corporate path
to a compassionate person?

00:38:13.370 --> 00:38:18.210
Is that someone else bringing
it to your attention?

00:38:18.210 --> 00:38:20.960
GARETH CHICK: It was a
very interesting moment.

00:38:20.960 --> 00:38:28.130
So I was 29, and I was a CFO
of a public company in the UK.

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:30.620
And I'd been a CFO for
public since I was 25--

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:32.637
the youngest youngest ever.

00:38:32.637 --> 00:38:34.970
I was the youngest ever this
and the youngest ever that.

00:38:34.970 --> 00:38:36.650
And I was married.

00:38:36.650 --> 00:38:38.070
I had two children.

00:38:38.070 --> 00:38:39.500
I had a four bedroom house.

00:38:39.500 --> 00:38:44.390
I mean, I was the
archetypal career driven--

00:38:44.390 --> 00:38:47.180
I was a nightmare, really.

00:38:47.180 --> 00:38:48.470
I was.

00:38:48.470 --> 00:38:50.900
And my boss-- chief
exec at the time,

00:38:50.900 --> 00:38:53.060
he was brilliant-- he
took me to one side

00:38:53.060 --> 00:38:55.410
and gave me some
really tough feedback.

00:38:55.410 --> 00:39:03.690
And he said, you're good,
but you are about to fail.

00:39:03.690 --> 00:39:06.440
I'm going to send you
on a leadership course.

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:11.320
I cannot tell you how
cynical I was when I--

00:39:11.320 --> 00:39:13.820
It is part of the reason I do
the trainings and these moves.

00:39:13.820 --> 00:39:16.010
It's the part of the reason
I do the training now,

00:39:16.010 --> 00:39:18.350
because I know what
it's like, and I

00:39:18.350 --> 00:39:21.290
know how I was sitting in
training, thinking, come on,

00:39:21.290 --> 00:39:24.170
yeah, I know all this, or
you don't know how busy I am.

00:39:24.170 --> 00:39:25.280
I would do all of that.

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:28.100
He sent me on this course,
and I behaved very badly

00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:30.470
on the first morning.

00:39:30.470 --> 00:39:33.980
I was cynical, and I was surly,
and I was looking at my watch,

00:39:33.980 --> 00:39:36.663
and yeah, yeah, and we didn't
have email in those days.

00:39:36.663 --> 00:39:38.330
But I would have been
the one constantly

00:39:38.330 --> 00:39:40.590
checking the phone, not
really engaged, and saying,

00:39:40.590 --> 00:39:41.930
oh just, you know,
I'm really sorry,

00:39:41.930 --> 00:39:43.690
but I've got to jump on
a call for half an hour.

00:39:43.690 --> 00:39:45.430
I'll come back, and
then it's an hour.

00:39:45.430 --> 00:39:47.150
I would that would
have been that person.

00:39:47.150 --> 00:39:49.080
My instructor,
Walter Blackburn--

00:39:49.080 --> 00:39:52.250
he's acknowledged in
the front of the book--

00:39:52.250 --> 00:39:55.910
and he saw this, and
he took me to one side.

00:39:55.910 --> 00:39:58.310
He metaphorically stuck
his hand under my chin

00:39:58.310 --> 00:40:03.640
and put me up against the wall
and said, you need to grow up,

00:40:03.640 --> 00:40:05.310
or you need to go.

00:40:05.310 --> 00:40:09.360
But if you're going to stay
here, you need to get involved.

00:40:09.360 --> 00:40:12.040
I don't think anybody really
spoken to me like that before.

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:14.460
He knew what he was doing.

00:40:14.460 --> 00:40:18.200
He knew how to do that
with me in a way that

00:40:18.200 --> 00:40:19.520
would win my respect.

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:22.940
That was a turning point,
because I threw myself in.

00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:25.310
And the reason I had
this crazy, you know,

00:40:25.310 --> 00:40:29.300
full time CEO whatever and
part-time leadership trainer is

00:40:29.300 --> 00:40:33.490
partly why my first marriage
didn't last that long-- well,

00:40:33.490 --> 00:40:36.380
and I was a bit of an asshole--

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:42.200
that is why then I asked to go
and learn how to train others

00:40:42.200 --> 00:40:44.310
with that course.

00:40:44.310 --> 00:40:47.180
I became evangelistic
about coaching.

00:40:47.180 --> 00:40:50.300
It really taught me some
emotional intelligence,

00:40:50.300 --> 00:40:51.710
and it taught me how to coach.

00:40:51.710 --> 00:40:55.820
It taught me that beautiful
transformational moment

00:40:55.820 --> 00:41:00.410
as a coach, when you
can have a person--

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:05.780
you can release all of that
potential, and ingenuity,

00:41:05.780 --> 00:41:08.960
and humanity they
have, and they will

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:11.570
perform to an even higher
level, because that's

00:41:11.570 --> 00:41:12.760
what they want to do.

00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:13.260
Yeah.

00:41:13.260 --> 00:41:15.530
It was transformational.

00:41:15.530 --> 00:41:17.840
AUDIENCE: You talk
about people with drive.

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:20.010
And you said, it's aggression.

00:41:20.010 --> 00:41:20.760
GARETH CHICK: Yes.

00:41:20.760 --> 00:41:23.360
AUDIENCE: Sound like
kind of picturing them

00:41:23.360 --> 00:41:24.470
in a negative way.

00:41:24.470 --> 00:41:24.970
If we were--

00:41:24.970 --> 00:41:25.803
GARETH CHICK: I was.

00:41:25.803 --> 00:41:29.690
AUDIENCE: --all more
human as you suggest,

00:41:29.690 --> 00:41:32.500
do you think the corporations
would be more efficient or less

00:41:32.500 --> 00:41:35.000
efficient?

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:36.720
GARETH CHICK: Absolutely
more efficient.

00:41:36.720 --> 00:41:38.510
I've had some
interesting conversations

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:41.870
with some senior Google leaders
about psychological safety,

00:41:41.870 --> 00:41:43.730
for example.

00:41:43.730 --> 00:41:47.010
And every one of them says our
psychological safety really,

00:41:47.010 --> 00:41:48.460
really important.

00:41:48.460 --> 00:41:50.420
And when I asked
them to describe

00:41:50.420 --> 00:41:55.340
what behaviors they
exhibit to actively create

00:41:55.340 --> 00:41:57.320
psychological
safety, they struggle

00:41:57.320 --> 00:42:00.860
to tell me those things.

00:42:00.860 --> 00:42:03.982
They make it sound really
great, but it goes on

00:42:03.982 --> 00:42:04.940
for about five minutes.

00:42:04.940 --> 00:42:07.760
And I have really no
idea what they've said,

00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:10.700
because they haven't really
answered the question.

00:42:10.700 --> 00:42:13.270
And then I say how
do you measure it?

00:42:13.270 --> 00:42:15.770
And they say, well, we have
this Google guy stand, you know,

00:42:15.770 --> 00:42:16.440
whatever.

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:16.940
OK.

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:20.270
Which questions actually show me
that you have a psychologically

00:42:20.270 --> 00:42:22.505
safe workforce?

00:42:22.505 --> 00:42:23.240
Ah, Well.

00:42:25.770 --> 00:42:29.570
So the reality is that
when we're on-- listen.

00:42:29.570 --> 00:42:34.430
You've got some fabulous
leaders, fabulous leaders,

00:42:34.430 --> 00:42:36.200
some of the best in the world.

00:42:36.200 --> 00:42:40.730
But they are also human, and
therefore, under pressure, they

00:42:40.730 --> 00:42:44.840
can flirt with some of those
corporapathic behaviors.

00:42:44.840 --> 00:42:46.580
And here's the issue.

00:42:46.580 --> 00:42:50.600
Under pressure, some
of those leaders

00:42:50.600 --> 00:42:53.840
are found out occasionally,
because here's

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:56.870
what I think internally.

00:42:56.870 --> 00:43:05.120
It's coming up to the end
of Q1, we're short of quota.

00:43:05.120 --> 00:43:11.510
If I make people feel too safe,
then they'll go a bit soft.

00:43:11.510 --> 00:43:13.000
They will breathe
a sigh of relief.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:14.870
They will realize that
they're quite tired,

00:43:14.870 --> 00:43:16.670
and that's my quota gone.

00:43:16.670 --> 00:43:21.770
So actually I can't have
people feeling too safe.

00:43:21.770 --> 00:43:23.400
I don't want you
to feel threatened.

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:24.990
I don't want them
to feel fearful.

00:43:24.990 --> 00:43:28.550
Well, you can't have one or the
other, because you hold power.

00:43:28.550 --> 00:43:34.820
If I hold power, I don't need to
do anything to intimidate you,

00:43:34.820 --> 00:43:36.320
because I have power.

00:43:36.320 --> 00:43:39.150
I have to massively
over index on that.

00:43:39.150 --> 00:43:41.960
So there are countless
examples I could give you

00:43:41.960 --> 00:43:46.040
of where true psychological
safety delivers

00:43:46.040 --> 00:43:50.240
phenomenal results, because
people, when they feel safe,

00:43:50.240 --> 00:43:52.160
they get incredibly creative.

00:43:52.160 --> 00:43:54.980
You don't hire dullards.

00:43:54.980 --> 00:43:59.240
You hire brilliantly
well-qualified people.

00:43:59.240 --> 00:44:03.170
All they want to do
is do fabulous work.

00:44:03.170 --> 00:44:04.790
That's all they want to do.

00:44:04.790 --> 00:44:06.470
Leave them to
their own devices--

00:44:06.470 --> 00:44:08.210
bit of governance,
bit of coaching--

00:44:08.210 --> 00:44:11.310
just wear them what we have
to do for the millennials--

00:44:11.310 --> 00:44:13.110
and they will fly.

00:44:13.110 --> 00:44:15.242
We haven't begun to
see what people can do.

00:44:15.242 --> 00:44:17.700
Now, it's crazy thing to say--
and this organization that's

00:44:17.700 --> 00:44:20.160
only 20 years old, there's
now 100,000 of you,

00:44:20.160 --> 00:44:24.180
and you make $5 billion
every 10 minute.

00:44:24.180 --> 00:44:25.780
I understand that.

00:44:25.780 --> 00:44:29.310
But actually how long
will that continue?

00:44:29.310 --> 00:44:31.290
You've got competitors
taking share of you

00:44:31.290 --> 00:44:34.102
right, left, and center.

00:44:34.102 --> 00:44:36.920
I wonder.

00:44:36.920 --> 00:44:37.420
Thank you.

